---
import Base from '../../../layouts/Base.astro';
import Loader from '../../../components/Loader.astro';
import Cursor from '../../../components/Cursor.astro';
import Nav from '../../../components/Nav.astro';
import FsMenu from '../../../components/FsMenu.astro';
import Footer from '../../../components/Footer.astro';
import '../../../styles/global.css';
import '../../../styles/stories.css';
---

<Base title="Taylor Assessment — Basit Masood" description="The world's only culture-contribution psychometric, redesigned for a digital-first world. 30 behaviors, 6 archetypes. Press-released globally in January 2024.">

<script is:inline>
  (function(){
    var apply = function(){ document.body && document.body.classList.add('page-light'); };
    var clear = function(){ document.body && document.body.classList.remove('page-light'); };
    apply();
    document.addEventListener('astro:page-load', apply);
    document.addEventListener('astro:after-swap', apply);
    document.addEventListener('astro:before-swap', clear);
  })();
</script>

<Loader />
<Cursor />
<Nav active="stories" />
<FsMenu />

<!-- HERO -->
<section class="sp2-hero">
  <div class="sp2-hero-inner">
    <p class="sp2-hero-eyebrow">
      <a href="/stories/wtt" style="color:inherit;text-decoration:none;">← Walking the Talk</a> · Case study · 2023 – 2024
    </p>
    <h1 class="sp2-hero-primary">Measuring culture at scale.</h1>
    <p class="sp2-hero-secondary">The world's only culture-contribution psychometric, redesigned.</p>
    <p class="sp2-hero-desc">Walking the Talk's Taylor Assessment is unique — the only psychometric that measures how an individual contributes to organizational culture. 30 behaviors, 6 archetypes. I redesigned the experience for a digital-first world while preserving the psychometric rigor that makes the tool credible. Press-released globally in January 2024.</p>
  </div>
  <span class="sp2-hero-scroll">Scroll</span>
</section>

<!-- BRAND MOMENT -->
<section class="sb-brand">
  <div class="sb-brand-inner">
    <img src="/images/WTT-full-logo.svg" alt="Walking the Talk" class="sb-brand-logo" />
    <div class="sb-brand-rule"></div>
    <p class="sb-brand-caption">Walking the Talk · Taylor Assessment · 2023 – 2024</p>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- CHALLENGE -->
<section class="sub-section">
  <div class="sub-section-inner">
    <span class="sub-section-label">Challenge</span>
    <div>
      <h2 class="sub-section-heading">Modern UX<br/>without <span class="accent">losing the science</span>.</h2>
      <div class="sub-section-body">
        <p>The Taylor Assessment is the only psychometric in the market measuring culture contribution — 30 behaviors across 6 archetypes (Achievement, Customer-Centric, One Team, Innovative, People First, Greater Good). But the existing tool was built for a pre-digital world. Long form pages, minimal feedback, results that required expert interpretation.</p>
        <p>In a world where leaders expect Spotify-level UX, it needed to meet modern expectations — without compromising the rigor that made it credible. You can't optimize UX at the expense of assessment accuracy.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- METRIC HIGHLIGHT -->
<section class="sub-highlight">
  <span class="sub-highlight-value">50K+</span>
  <span class="sub-highlight-label">Leaders assessed across 200+ organizations</span>
</section>

<!-- APPROACH -->
<section class="sub-section">
  <div class="sub-section-inner">
    <span class="sub-section-label">Approach</span>
    <div>
      <h2 class="sub-section-heading">Psychometric rigor.<br/>Untouched.</h2>
      <div class="sub-section-body">
        <p>I worked closely with Walking the Talk's psychometric experts and the Psynet platform team. Every question's presentation, ordering, and response mechanism had been calibrated over years of research — those elements couldn't change. Within that constraint, there was significant room to improve: visual design, progress feedback, transition animations, results presentation, overall flow.</p>
        <p>I designed the assessment as a journey, not a form. Each section — corresponding to a culture archetype — had its own visual identity within a cohesive whole. Progress was communicated through explicit indicators and subtle visual cues. Transitions between sections felt like moving through chapters of a story about yourself.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- PULL QUOTE -->
<section class="sub-pullquote">
  <div class="sub-pullquote-mark">&#8220;</div>
  <p class="sub-pullquote-text">Good design makes the science work better.</p>
  <p class="sub-pullquote-cite">The redesign thesis</p>
</section>

<!-- OUTCOME -->
<section class="sub-section">
  <div class="sub-section-inner">
    <span class="sub-section-label">Outcome</span>
    <div>
      <h2 class="sub-section-heading">Press-released globally.<br/>January 2024.</h2>
      <div class="sub-section-body">
        <p>A 30-minute experience that feels like personal discovery rather than form-filling. The results experience was completely reimagined — visual culture-contribution profiles readable in a glance, while still providing the depth that coaches and consultants needed. Team and organization-level views aggregate individual data into culture heat maps that reveal patterns invisible at the individual level.</p>
        <p>The redesigned Taylor Assessment was press-released globally in January 2024 and adopted by multinationals and government agencies. It proved that psychometric rigor and modern UX aren't in conflict — they're complementary.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- NEXT -->
<section class="sp2-next">
  <div class="sp2-next-back"><a href="/stories/wtt"><span class="sp2-arrow">←</span> Back to Walking the Talk</a></div>
  <a href="/stories/adib" class="sp2-next-cta">
    <span class="label">Next Story</span>
    <span class="title">ADIB <span class="sp2-arrow">→</span></span>
  </a>
</section>

<Footer />

<script>
  function initSub() {
    const io = new IntersectionObserver((entries) => {
      entries.forEach(e => {
        if (e.isIntersecting) { e.target.classList.add('revealed'); io.unobserve(e.target); }
      });
    }, { threshold: 0.08, rootMargin: '0px 0px -40px 0px' });
    document.querySelectorAll('.reveal').forEach(el => io.observe(el));
    if (window.matchMedia('(prefers-reduced-motion: reduce)').matches) {
      document.querySelectorAll('.reveal').forEach(el => el.classList.add('revealed'));
    }
  }
  initSub();
  document.addEventListener('astro:page-load', initSub);
</script>

</Base>
